export default {n:28,lang:"fr",srcLang:"en",track:"v2",title:"Convaincre et Argumenter",sub:"Essay structure and persuasion",icon:"💬",level:"B2.4",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[
  {id:"fre28l1",title:"Structurer ses idées",icon:"📋",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Structurer ses idées",desc:"Learn the essential sequencing markers that give your writing and speech a clear, logical flow.",goals:["Use d'abord, ensuite, puis, enfin","Structure a sequence of arguments","Recognize formal ordering markers"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"d'abord",src:"first / firstly",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"dah-BOR",note:"Introduces the first point in a sequence.",example:"A: Comment organises-tu tes idées?\nB: D'abord, je fais un plan détaillé.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you organize your ideas?\nB: First, I make a detailed plan.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"ensuite",src:"then / next",pos:"adv",gender:null,phonetic:"on-SWEET",note:"Marks the step that follows the first.",example:"A: Et après le plan?\nB: Ensuite, je rédige l'introduction.",exampleSrc:"A: And after the plan?\nB: Then, I write the introduction.",funFact:"French adverbs often end in -ment (like English -ly), formed from the feminine adjective."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"puis",src:"then / afterwards",pos:"adv",gender:null,phonetic:"PWEE",note:"Similar to ensuite but slightly more informal.",example:"A: Tu fais quoi après l'introduction?\nB: Puis, je développe chaque argument.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you do after the introduction?\nB: Then, I develop each argument.",funFact:"French adverbs often end in -ment (like English -ly), formed from the feminine adjective."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"enfin",src:"finally / lastly",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"on-FAN",note:"Signals the last element in a sequence.",example:"A: Et pour terminer?\nB: Enfin, je relis tout attentivement.",exampleSrc:"A: And to finish?\nB: Finally, I reread everything carefully.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"en premier lieu",src:"in the first place",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"on pruh-MYAY LYUH",note:"Formal alternative to d'abord. Common in essays.",example:"A: Par où commencer cette analyse?\nB: En premier lieu, examinons les causes du problème.",exampleSrc:"A: Where to start this analysis?\nB: In the first place, let's examine the causes of the problem.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Sequencing in French writing",text:"French values logical structure. Use sequencing markers to guide the reader:\n\n1. d'abord / en premier lieu (first)\n2. ensuite / puis (then)\n3. enfin / en dernier lieu (finally)\n\nIn formal writing, prefer en premier lieu over d'abord."},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which marker introduces the FIRST point in a sequence?",opts:["d'abord","ensuite","puis","enfin"],ans:"d'abord",hint:"Think about what comes at the very beginning."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["D'abord","Ensuite","Enfin","Puis"],hint:"We need the marker for the very first point.",s:"{1}, je voudrais remercier tous les participants.",a:["D'abord"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which expression is the MOST formal way to say 'firstly'?",opts:["d'abord","en premier lieu","puis","ensuite"],ans:"en premier lieu",hint:"This longer expression belongs in academic writing."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["puis","enfin","d'abord","en premier lieu"],hint:"We need a word meaning 'then' or 'next'.",s:"J'ai fait les courses, {1} j'ai préparé le dîner.",a:["puis","ensuite"]},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"d'abord",src:"first"},{trg:"ensuite",src:"then / next"},{trg:"puis",src:"then / afterwards"},{trg:"enfin",src:"finally"},{trg:"en premier lieu",src:"in the first place"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Enfin, je voudrais conclure par une question.' What does enfin signal here?",opts:["A contrast","The first point","The last point","A cause"],ans:"The last point",hint:"This marker wraps up a sequence."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Ensuite","Enfin","D'abord","En premier lieu"],hint:"This is a middle step, not the first or last.",s:"{1}, il faut analyser les résultats de l'enquête.",a:["Ensuite"]},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"First we examine context, then we analyze data.",s:"{1}, nous examinerons le contexte. {2}, nous analyserons les données.",blanks:{"1":"D'abord","2":"Ensuite"},pool:["D'abord","Ensuite","Enfin","Puis"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which pair of markers correctly frames a two-step sequence?",opts:["Ensuite... d'abord","Enfin... d'abord","Puis... en premier lieu","D'abord... ensuite"],ans:"D'abord... ensuite",hint:"The logical order starts from the beginning."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["En premier lieu","Puis","Enfin","Ensuite"],hint:"A formal way to introduce the very first point.",s:"{1}, je tiens à souligner l'importance de ce projet.",a:["En premier lieu"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"In the sentence 'Puis, il a expliqué sa méthode', what role does puis play?",opts:["It introduces the next step","It introduces the first step","It signals a contrast","It marks the conclusion"],ans:"It introduces the next step",hint:"This marker connects one action to the following one."},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"Order the three stages of a presentation logically.",s:"{1}, présentons le sujet. {2}, développons les arguments. {3}, tirons une conclusion.",blanks:{"1":"D'abord","2":"Ensuite","3":"Enfin"},pool:["D'abord","Ensuite","Enfin","Puis"]}
  ]},
  {id:"fre28l2",title:"Ajouter et contraster",icon:"⚖️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Ajouter et contraster",desc:"Master the markers that add information and introduce contrast, essential tools for balanced argumentation.",goals:["Use de plus, en outre, par ailleurs for addition","Use cependant, néanmoins, toutefois for contrast","Use en revanche for direct opposition"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"de plus",src:"moreover / furthermore",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"duh PLEW",note:"Adds a reinforcing argument to the previous one.",example:"A: Ce projet est rentable.\nB: De plus, il crée des emplois dans la région.",exampleSrc:"A: This project is profitable.\nB: Moreover, it creates jobs in the region.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"en outre",src:"furthermore / in addition",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"on OOTR",note:"Very formal. Common in academic and official writing.",example:"A: Les résultats sont encourageants.\nB: En outre, ils dépassent nos prévisions initiales.",exampleSrc:"A: The results are encouraging.\nB: Furthermore, they exceed our initial forecasts.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"par ailleurs",src:"moreover / besides",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"par ay-YUHR",note:"Adds a new but related point. Slightly shifts topic.",example:"A: Elle parle trois langues.\nB: Par ailleurs, elle a vécu dans cinq pays différents.",exampleSrc:"A: She speaks three languages.\nB: Besides, she has lived in five different countries.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"cependant",src:"however / nevertheless",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"suh-pon-DON",note:"Introduces a contrasting point. Very common in essays.",example:"A: Le plan semble parfait.\nB: Cependant, il reste plusieurs obstacles à surmonter.",exampleSrc:"A: The plan seems perfect.\nB: However, there are still several obstacles to overcome.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"néanmoins",src:"nevertheless / nonetheless",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"nay-on-MWAN",note:"Formal synonym of cependant. Shows concession.",example:"A: Les critiques sont nombreuses.\nB: Néanmoins, le projet a reçu un soutien massif.",exampleSrc:"A: There are many criticisms.\nB: Nevertheless, the project received massive support.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"toutefois",src:"however / yet",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"toot-FWAH",note:"Elegant contrast marker. Preferred in formal registers.",example:"A: Cette solution est efficace.\nB: Toutefois, son coût reste un problème majeur.",exampleSrc:"A: This solution is effective.\nB: Yet, its cost remains a major problem.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"en revanche",src:"on the other hand",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"on ruh-VONSH",note:"Marks direct opposition between two facts.",example:"A: Le nord du pays est industriel.\nB: En revanche, le sud est surtout agricole.",exampleSrc:"A: The north of the country is industrial.\nB: On the other hand, the south is mainly agricultural.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Addition vs. Contrast",text:"Addition markers stack arguments:\n. de plus, en outre, par ailleurs\n\nContrast markers introduce opposition:\n. cependant, néanmoins, toutefois\n\nDirect opposition uses en revanche.\n\nIn essays, alternate addition and contrast for balanced arguments."},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which marker adds a REINFORCING argument?",opts:["de plus","cependant","en revanche","toutefois"],ans:"de plus",hint:"We want to pile on another supporting point."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Cependant","De plus","En outre","Par ailleurs"],hint:"We need a word that introduces a contrasting fact.",s:"Le chômage a baissé. {1}, les inégalités persistent.",a:["Cependant","Néanmoins","Toutefois"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which is the MOST formal addition marker?",opts:["de plus","en outre","par ailleurs","aussi"],ans:"en outre",hint:"This expression is typical of official documents."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"de plus",src:"moreover"},{trg:"cependant",src:"however"},{trg:"en revanche",src:"on the other hand"},{trg:"néanmoins",src:"nevertheless"},{trg:"en outre",src:"furthermore"}]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Par ailleurs","Cependant","Néanmoins","En revanche"],hint:"We are adding a related but slightly different point.",s:"Paris est une ville culturelle. {1}, Lyon offre aussi une vie artistique riche.",a:["Par ailleurs"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Toutefois, cette mesure a des limites.' What does toutefois express?",opts:["A cause","An addition","A contrast or reservation","A conclusion"],ans:"A contrast or reservation",hint:"The sentence introduces a limit to something positive."},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"First add a positive point, then introduce a drawback.",s:"Ce produit est innovant. {1}, il est écologique. {2}, son prix est élevé.",blanks:{"1":"De plus","2":"Toutefois"},pool:["De plus","Toutefois","Enfin","D'abord"]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["En revanche","De plus","En outre","Par ailleurs"],hint:"We directly oppose two modes of transport.",s:"Le train est rapide. {1}, l'avion reste plus pratique pour les longues distances.",a:["En revanche"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which marker would best complete: 'Les ventes ont augmenté. ___, les bénéfices restent faibles.'?",opts:["Par ailleurs","De plus","En outre","Néanmoins"],ans:"Néanmoins",hint:"Sales are up but profits are not following suit."}
  ]},
  {id:"fre28l3",title:"Cause et conséquence",icon:"🔗",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Cause et conséquence",desc:"Connect ideas with markers that explain WHY something happens and WHAT results from it.",goals:["Use en effet, car, puisque for cause","Use c'est pourquoi, par conséquent, d'où for consequence","Distinguish formal from informal registers"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"en effet",src:"indeed / in fact",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"on eh-FEH",note:"Confirms and explains the previous statement.",example:"A: Tu penses que ce restaurant est bon?\nB: En effet, il a reçu deux étoiles Michelin.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you think this restaurant is good?\nB: Indeed, it has received two Michelin stars.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"car",src:"because / for",pos:"conj",gender:null,phonetic:"KAR",note:"Introduces a cause. Used mid-sentence after a comma.",example:"A: Pourquoi ferme-t-on le parc?\nB: Le parc est fermé, car des travaux sont en cours.",exampleSrc:"A: Why is the park closing?\nB: The park is closed, because construction work is underway.",funFact:"French conjunctions affect the mood of the following verb. Some trigger the subjunctive."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"puisque",src:"since / given that",pos:"conj",gender:null,phonetic:"pwees-KUH",note:"The cause is already known or obvious to both speakers.",example:"A: Pourquoi ne pas prendre le bus?\nB: Puisque tu as une voiture, allons-y en voiture.",exampleSrc:"A: Why not take the bus?\nB: Since you have a car, let's go by car.",funFact:"French conjunctions affect the mood of the following verb. Some trigger the subjunctive."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"c'est pourquoi",src:"that is why",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"seh poor-KWAH",note:"Introduces a consequence. Always starts a new clause.",example:"A: Il pleut beaucoup cette semaine.\nB: C'est pourquoi les rivières sont en crue.",exampleSrc:"A: It is raining a lot this week.\nB: That is why the rivers are flooding.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"par conséquent",src:"consequently / therefore",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"par kon-say-KON",note:"Very formal consequence marker. Common in reports.",example:"A: Le budget a été réduit.\nB: Par conséquent, certains projets seront reportés.",exampleSrc:"A: The budget has been reduced.\nB: Consequently, some projects will be postponed.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"d'où",src:"hence / from which",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"DOO",note:"Compact consequence marker. Often followed by a noun.",example:"A: Les résultats sont décevants.\nB: D'où la nécessité de revoir notre stratégie.",exampleSrc:"A: The results are disappointing.\nB: Hence the need to review our strategy.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Cause vs. Consequence flow",text:"Cause markers explain WHY:\n. en effet (confirms/explains)\n. car (because, mid-sentence)\n. puisque (since, known reason)\n\nConsequence markers show WHAT RESULTS:\n. c'est pourquoi (that is why)\n. par conséquent (consequently)\n. d'où (hence)\n\nPattern: Fact + cause marker + reason\nOR: Fact + consequence marker + result"},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which marker introduces a cause that is already known to both speakers?",opts:["puisque","car","en effet","c'est pourquoi"],ans:"puisque",hint:"The reason is obvious or previously established."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["C'est pourquoi","En effet","Car","Puisque"],hint:"The cold weather leads to a recommendation.",s:"Il fait froid dehors. {1}, n'oublie pas ton manteau.",a:["C'est pourquoi","Par conséquent"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Le musée est gratuit le dimanche, car l'État finance l'entrée.' What does car do here?",opts:["It introduces a consequence","It explains the reason","It adds information","It contrasts two ideas"],ans:"It explains the reason",hint:"The clause after this word tells us why it is free."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"en effet",src:"indeed"},{trg:"car",src:"because"},{trg:"puisque",src:"since"},{trg:"c'est pourquoi",src:"that is why"},{trg:"par conséquent",src:"consequently"}]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Puisque","Car","C'est pourquoi","Par conséquent"],hint:"The readiness is obvious, so we state the known reason.",s:"{1} tu es déjà prêt, nous pouvons partir.",a:["Puisque"]},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"First a consequence, then a resulting necessity.",s:"La demande a augmenté. {1}, les prix ont grimpé. {2}, il faut trouver de nouveaux fournisseurs.",blanks:{"1":"Par conséquent","2":"D'où"},pool:["Par conséquent","D'où","Car","Puisque"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which marker is typically followed by a NOUN phrase rather than a full clause?",opts:["par conséquent","c'est pourquoi","d'où","en effet"],ans:"d'où",hint:"Think of 'd'ou la necessite de...' with a noun after it."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["En effet","D'où","C'est pourquoi","Puisque"],hint:"We are confirming and explaining why it is effective.",s:"Ce médicament est efficace. {1}, il est recommandé par les médecins.",a:["En effet"]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["c'est pourquoi","en effet","car","puisque"],hint:"This marker introduces a direct logical consequence of what was stated.",s:"Les transports sont en grève, {1} les employés doivent trouver des alternatives.",a:["c'est pourquoi"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Choose the correct cause marker: 'Nous restons chez nous, ___ il neige.'",opts:["d'où","c'est pourquoi","par conséquent","car"],ans:"car",hint:"We need to explain the reason for staying home."}
  ]},
  {id:"fre28l4",title:"La concession",icon:"🤝",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"La concession",desc:"Learn to acknowledge opposing points while maintaining your argument, a hallmark of sophisticated French writing.",goals:["Use bien que + subjonctif","Use même si + indicatif","Master certes...mais and malgré","Distinguish concession from simple contrast"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"bien que + subjonctif",src:"although (+ subjunctive)",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"byaN KUH",note:"Always followed by the subjunctive. Very formal.",example:"A: Tu sors par ce temps?\nB: Bien que le temps soit mauvais, je dois aller travailler.",exampleSrc:"A: You're going out in this weather?\nB: Although the weather is bad, I have to go to work.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"même si + indicatif",src:"even if (+ indicative)",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"mem SEE",note:"Takes the indicative, unlike bien que. Less formal.",example:"A: Et si le projet échoue?\nB: Même si le projet échoue, nous aurons beaucoup appris.",exampleSrc:"A: And if the project fails?\nB: Even if the project fails, we will have learned a lot.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"malgré",src:"despite / in spite of",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"mal-GRAY",note:"Followed by a noun, never a conjugated verb.",example:"A: Il a réussi facilement?\nB: Non, mais malgré les difficultés, il a obtenu son diplôme.",exampleSrc:"A: Did he succeed easily?\nB: No, but despite the difficulties, he obtained his degree.",funFact:"French verbs change form for each person. The spoken forms are often simpler than the written ones."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"certes... mais",src:"admittedly... but",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"SEHRT... MEH",note:"Acknowledges the opponent's point, then counters.",example:"A: Ce plan a des avantages, non?\nB: Certes, il est ambitieux, mais il manque de réalisme.",exampleSrc:"A: This plan has advantages, right?\nB: Admittedly, it is ambitious, but it lacks realism.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"quoique",src:"although / though",pos:"conj",gender:null,phonetic:"kwah-KUH",note:"Formal synonym of bien que. Also takes subjunctive.",example:"A: Tu aimes ce quartier?\nB: Quoique bruyant, ce quartier a beaucoup de charme.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like this neighborhood?\nB: Although noisy, this neighborhood has a lot of charm.",funFact:"French conjunctions affect the mood of the following verb. Some trigger the subjunctive."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Concession: acknowledging before countering",text:"Concession means admitting the other side has a point, then presenting yours:\n\n. bien que / quoique + SUBJUNCTIVE (formal)\n. meme si + INDICATIVE (less formal)\n. malgre + NOUN (no verb)\n. certes... mais (admittedly... but)\n\nConcession is NOT simple contrast. It shows intellectual honesty in argumentation."},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which concession marker requires the SUBJUNCTIVE?",opts:["bien que","même si","malgré","certes"],ans:"bien que",hint:"This formal marker triggers a special verb mood."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Malgré","Bien que","Même si","Certes"],hint:"We need a word followed by a noun, not a verb.",s:"{1} les obstacles, elle a terminé le marathon.",a:["Malgré"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Même si tu n'es pas d'accord, écoute son argument.' Why is the indicative used here?",opts:["Because it is informal","Because même si takes the indicative","Because it expresses a wish","Because the subject is tu"],ans:"Because même si takes the indicative",hint:"This concession marker has a grammatical rule about mood."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Bien que","Même si","Malgré","Certes"],hint:"We need a marker that triggers the subjunctive mood.",s:"{1} le prix soit élevé, la qualité en vaut la peine.",a:["Bien que","Quoique"]},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"First acknowledge the drawback, then counter it.",s:"{1}, ce restaurant est cher, {2} la cuisine est exceptionnelle.",blanks:{"1":"Certes","2":"mais"},pool:["Certes","mais","malgré","bien que"]},
        {type:"match",pairs:[
          {trg:"bien que",src:"although (+ subj.)"},
          {trg:"même si",src:"even if (+ indic.)"},
          {trg:"malgré",src:"despite (+ noun)"},
          {trg:"certes... mais",src:"admittedly... but"},
          {trg:"quoique",src:"although (formal)"}
        ]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which is correct: 'Malgré ___ la pluie, nous sommes sortis'?",opts:["il (malgré il pleut)","que (malgré que la pluie)","No word needed (malgré la pluie)","de (malgré de la pluie)"],ans:"No word needed (malgré la pluie)",hint:"This marker connects directly to a noun phrase."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Quoique","Même si","Malgré","Certes"],hint:"A formal marker requiring the subjunctive of faire.",s:"{1} il fasse froid, les enfants jouent dehors.",a:["Quoique","Bien que"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which marker means \"although\" and requires the subjunctive?",opts:["certes","même si","malgré","bien que"],ans:"bien que",hint:"This two-word conjunction is followed by a verb form expressing doubt or subjectivity."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Malgré","Bien que","Même si","Quoique"],hint:"This preposition is followed directly by a noun, not a conjugated verb.",s:"{1} ses efforts, il n'a pas réussi à convaincre le jury.",a:["Malgré"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"In argumentation, what does concession achieve?",opts:["It shows you understand the opposing view","It proves the opponent is wrong","It changes the subject","It repeats your main point"],ans:"It shows you understand the opposing view",hint:"Good debaters acknowledge the other side first."}
  ]},
  {id:"fre28l5",title:"La dissertation française",icon:"📝",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"La dissertation française",desc:"Master the classic French essay structure used in schools, universities, and competitive exams.",goals:["Understand the dissertation format","Structure introduction, body, and conclusion","Use transitional phrases between sections"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"la thèse",src:"the thesis / argument for",pos:"noun",gender:"f",phonetic:"lah TEZ",note:"First part of the body. Defends one side.",example:"A: C'est quoi la thèse dans une dissertation?\nB: La thèse présente les arguments en faveur du sujet.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the thesis in a dissertation?\nB: The thesis presents the arguments in favor of the subject.",funFact:"Feminine noun. Words ending in -tion, -sion, -ure are usually feminine."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"l'antithèse",src:"the antithesis / counter-argument",pos:"noun",gender:"m",phonetic:"lon-tee-TEZ",note:"Second part. Presents the other side honestly.",example:"A: Et après la thèse?\nB: L'antithèse examine les arguments opposés.",exampleSrc:"A: And after the thesis?\nB: The antithesis examines the opposing arguments.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"la synthèse",src:"the synthesis / resolution",pos:"noun",gender:"f",phonetic:"lah san-TEZ",note:"Third part. Resolves the debate with a balanced view.",example:"A: Comment conclure le développement?\nB: La synthèse propose une vision nuancée qui dépasse l'opposition.",exampleSrc:"A: How to conclude the body?\nB: The synthesis proposes a nuanced view that goes beyond the opposition.",funFact:"Feminine noun. Words ending in -tion, -sion, -ure are usually feminine."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"poser la problématique",src:"to state the central question",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"poh-ZAY lah prob-lay-mah-TEEK",note:"The introduction must end with a clear question.",example:"A: Que fait-on dans l'introduction?\nB: On doit poser la problématique clairement.",exampleSrc:"A: What do we do in the introduction?\nB: We must state the central question clearly.",funFact:"French verbs change form for each person. The spoken forms are often simpler than the written ones."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"annoncer le plan",src:"to outline the structure",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"ah-non-SAY luh PLON",note:"The last sentence of the introduction previews the essay's parts.",example:"A: Il faut annoncer le plan?\nB: Oui, toujours. Le lecteur doit savoir où vous allez.",exampleSrc:"A: Do we need to outline the structure?\nB: Yes, always. The reader must know where you are going.",funFact:"French verbs change form for each person. The spoken forms are often simpler than the written ones."},
        {type:"tip",title:"The dissertation structure",text:"The French dissertation follows a strict plan:\n\n1. Introduction: context, central question, plan outline\n2. Thèse: arguments FOR the position\n3. Antithèse: arguments AGAINST\n4. Synthèse: balanced resolution, new perspective\n5. Conclusion: summary, answer, opening question\n\nThis structure is taught from high school through university."},
        {type:"mc",q:"In a French dissertation, what comes AFTER the thèse?",opts:["L'antithèse","La synthèse","La conclusion","L'introduction"],ans:"L'antithèse",hint:"The opposing arguments follow the supporting ones."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["poser la problématique","annoncer le plan","écrire la synthèse","présenter l'antithèse"],hint:"The introduction must present the central question.",s:"Dans l'introduction, il faut {1} clairement.",a:["poser la problématique"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"What is the role of the synthèse?",opts:["To repeat the thèse","To resolve the debate with a nuanced view","To reject the antithèse","To introduce new evidence"],ans:"To resolve the debate with a nuanced view",hint:"This section goes beyond simple for/against."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[
          {trg:"la thèse",src:"arguments for"},
          {trg:"l'antithèse",src:"counter-arguments"},
          {trg:"la synthèse",src:"balanced resolution"},
          {trg:"poser la problématique",src:"state the question"},
          {trg:"annoncer le plan",src:"outline the structure"}
        ]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["annoncer le plan","poser la problématique","écrire la synthèse","rejeter l'antithèse"],hint:"The reader needs a preview of what is coming next.",s:"La dernière phrase de l'introduction doit {1}.",a:["annoncer le plan"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Why does the dissertation include an antithèse?",opts:["To confuse the reader","To prove the thèse is wrong","To show intellectual honesty by examining both sides","To add length to the essay"],ans:"To show intellectual honesty by examining both sides",hint:"Good argumentation considers opposing viewpoints."},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"The two opposing sections come before the resolution.",s:"La dissertation suit le plan: introduction, {1}, {2}, synthèse, conclusion.",blanks:{"1":"thèse","2":"antithèse"},pool:["thèse","antithèse","synthèse","conclusion"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"A French dissertation introduction typically ends with:",opts:["A list of sources","A personal anecdote","The conclusion","A clear statement of the plan"],ans:"A clear statement of the plan",hint:"The reader must know the structure before the body begins."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["synthèse","thèse","antithèse","conclusion"],hint:"This section creates a balanced resolution.",s:"La {1} propose une vision qui dépasse l'opposition entre thèse et antithèse.",a:["synthèse"]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["antithèse","synthèse","introduction","conclusion"],hint:"This section presents the counterarguments that challenge the initial position.",s:"Dans la {1}, on confronte la thèse avec des arguments opposés.",a:["antithèse"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which order is correct for the dissertation body?",opts:["Thèse, antithèse, synthèse","Antithèse, thèse, synthèse","Synthèse, thèse, antithèse","Thèse, synthèse, antithèse"],ans:"Thèse, antithèse, synthèse",hint:"Start with support, then opposition, then resolution."}
  ]},
  {id:"fre28l6",title:"Le vocabulaire de l'argumentation",icon:"🗣️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Le vocabulaire de l'argumentation",desc:"Build your arsenal of verbs and expressions for presenting, defending, and challenging arguments.",goals:["Use soutenir, affirmer, réfuter","Master nuancer, conclure, avancer","Apply argumentative verbs in context"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"soutenir",src:"to support / to argue",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"soo-tuh-NEER",note:"To defend a position with arguments. Formal register.",example:"A: Quelle est sa position?\nB: Il soutient que l'éducation doit être gratuite.",exampleSrc:"A: What is his position?\nB: He argues that education should be free.",funFact:"A -ir verb. Many follow the -ir pattern with -iss- in plural forms."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"affirmer",src:"to state / to assert",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"ah-feer-MAY",note:"Stronger than dire. Implies confidence in the claim.",example:"A: Que dit le rapport?\nB: Le rapport affirme que la situation s'améliore.",exampleSrc:"A: What does the report say?\nB: The report asserts that the situation is improving.",funFact:"A regular -er verb, the most common French verb group (~90% of all verbs)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"réfuter",src:"to refute / to disprove",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"ray-few-TAY",note:"To systematically prove an argument wrong.",example:"A: Et les critiques?\nB: L'auteur réfute ces arguments point par point.",exampleSrc:"A: And the criticisms?\nB: The author refutes these arguments point by point.",funFact:"A regular -er verb, the most common French verb group (~90% of all verbs)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"nuancer",src:"to nuance / to qualify",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"new-on-SAY",note:"To add subtlety. Shows intellectual sophistication.",example:"A: Tu es entièrement d'accord?\nB: Je voudrais nuancer cette affirmation.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you fully agree?\nB: I would like to qualify that statement.",funFact:"A regular -er verb, the most common French verb group (~90% of all verbs)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"conclure",src:"to conclude",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"kon-KLOOR",note:"Signals the final summary of an argument.",example:"A: Comment finir cette présentation?\nB: Pour conclure, je dirais que le bilan est positif.",exampleSrc:"A: How to finish this presentation?\nB: To conclude, I would say the outcome is positive.",funFact:"Cognate with English 'to conclude'. Many English words were borrowed from French after 1066."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"avancer",src:"to put forward / to advance",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"ah-von-SAY",note:"To propose an idea for consideration. Less forceful than affirmer.",example:"A: As-tu une idée nouvelle?\nB: Je voudrais avancer une hypothèse différente.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a new idea?\nB: I would like to put forward a different hypothesis.",funFact:"A regular -er verb, the most common French verb group (~90% of all verbs)."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Verbs of argumentation: a spectrum",text:"From weakest to strongest claim:\n\n. avancer (put forward, suggest)\n. soutenir (support, argue for)\n. affirmer (assert, state firmly)\n. réfuter (disprove, counter)\n\nTo show balance: nuancer (qualify, add nuance)\nTo wrap up: conclure (conclude, summarize)"},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which verb means to systematically prove an argument wrong?",opts:["réfuter","nuancer","avancer","soutenir"],ans:"réfuter",hint:"Think of dismantling an argument piece by piece."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["soutient","réfute","conclut","nuance"],hint:"The author is defending a position with arguments.",s:"L'auteur {1} que cette théorie est incomplète.",a:["soutient"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which verb adds subtlety to a bold claim?",opts:["affirmer","nuancer","réfuter","conclure"],ans:"nuancer",hint:"This verb makes a statement more balanced and careful."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"soutenir",src:"to argue / support"},{trg:"affirmer",src:"to assert"},{trg:"réfuter",src:"to refute"},{trg:"nuancer",src:"to nuance"},{trg:"conclure",src:"to conclude"}]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["conclure","réfuter","avancer","affirmer"],hint:"We are wrapping up and giving a final statement.",s:"Pour {1}, je dirais que les deux positions ont du mérite.",a:["conclure"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Je voudrais avancer une hypothèse.' How strong is this claim?",opts:["Weak: just guessing","Very strong: asserting a fact","Moderate: suggesting for consideration","Aggressive: attacking the opponent"],ans:"Moderate: suggesting for consideration",hint:"This verb proposes without imposing."},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"First a theory is proposed, then others disprove it.",s:"Le chercheur {1} une théorie. Ses collègues la {2}.",blanks:{"1":"avance","2":"réfutent"},pool:["avance","réfutent","nuance","conclut"]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["affirme","nuance","avance","conclut"],hint:"The minister is making a confident, firm statement.",s:"Le ministre {1} avec force que la réforme est nécessaire.",a:["affirme"]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["réfuter","soutenir","avancer","nuancer"],hint:"To disprove or counter someone's reasoning with evidence.",s:"Le député a tenté de {1} les arguments de son adversaire avec des statistiques.",a:["réfuter"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"In an essay, when would you use nuancer?",opts:["When listing facts","When starting the introduction","When rejecting an argument entirely","When qualifying a statement to show it is not absolute"],ans:"When qualifying a statement to show it is not absolute",hint:"This verb prevents your writing from being too black-and-white."}
  ]},
  {id:"fre28l7",title:"Le débat formel",icon:"🎤",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Le débat formel",desc:"Master the expressions used in formal debates, presentations, and academic discussions.",goals:["Use à mon avis, selon moi, il me semble que","Express agreement and disagreement formally","Structure a persuasive oral argument"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"à mon avis",src:"in my opinion",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"ah mon ah-VEE",note:"Common way to introduce personal opinion. Semi-formal.",example:"A: Que penses-tu de cette loi?\nB: À mon avis, cette loi est nécessaire mais insuffisante.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you think of this law?\nB: In my opinion, this law is necessary but insufficient.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"selon moi",src:"according to me / in my view",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"suh-LON MWAH",note:"Slightly more formal than 'a mon avis'.",example:"A: Le projet va réussir?\nB: Selon moi, le projet a de bonnes chances de succès.",exampleSrc:"A: Will the project succeed?\nB: In my view, the project has good chances of success.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"il me semble que",src:"it seems to me that",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"eel muh SOMBL kuh",note:"Softens the opinion. Shows humility in debate.",example:"A: L'économie va mieux?\nB: Il me semble que la reprise est encore fragile.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the economy doing better?\nB: It seems to me that the recovery is still fragile.",funFact:"French verbs change form for each person. The spoken forms are often simpler than the written ones."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"force est de constater que",src:"one must acknowledge that",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"FORS eh duh kon-stah-TAY kuh",note:"Very formal. Presents a fact as undeniable.",example:"A: Les résultats sont clairs?\nB: Force est de constater que les chiffres parlent d'eux-mêmes.",exampleSrc:"A: Are the results clear?\nB: One must acknowledge that the numbers speak for themselves.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"je suis convaincu que",src:"I am convinced that",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"zhuh swee kon-van-KOO kuh",note:"Strong personal conviction. Use in conclusions.",example:"A: Tu hésites encore?\nB: Non, je suis convaincu que c'est la bonne décision.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you still hesitating?\nB: No, I am convinced that it is the right decision.",funFact:"French verbs change form for each person. The spoken forms are often simpler than the written ones."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Expressing opinions: a formality scale",text:"From softest to strongest:\n\n. il me semble que (it seems to me)\n. a mon avis / selon moi (in my opinion)\n. je suis convaincu que (I am convinced)\n. force est de constater (one must acknowledge)\n\nIn debates, start soft and build to stronger claims. Never start with your strongest position."},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which expression is the SOFTEST way to introduce an opinion?",opts:["il me semble que","force est de constater que","je suis convaincu que","à mon avis"],ans:"il me semble que",hint:"This phrase shows humility and leaves room for doubt."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["À mon avis","Force est de constater que","Il me semble que","Je suis convaincu que"],hint:"A standard way to introduce a personal opinion.",s:"{1}, cette politique a plus d'inconvénients que d'avantages.",a:["À mon avis","Selon moi"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"When would you use 'force est de constater que'?",opts:["When expressing a personal preference","When presenting an undeniable fact","When disagreeing politely","When asking a question"],ans:"When presenting an undeniable fact",hint:"This expression implies the evidence is overwhelming."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[
          {trg:"à mon avis",src:"in my opinion"},
          {trg:"selon moi",src:"in my view"},
          {trg:"il me semble que",src:"it seems to me"},
          {trg:"force est de constater",src:"one must acknowledge"},
          {trg:"je suis convaincu que",src:"I am convinced"}
        ]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Il me semble que","Force est de constater que","Je suis convaincu que","À mon avis"],hint:"We want to express a cautious, humble observation.",s:"{1} la situation est plus complexe qu'il n'y paraît.",a:["Il me semble que"]},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"First state an undeniable fact, then express strong conviction.",s:"{1}, le problème est réel. {2} nous devons agir maintenant.",blanks:{"1":"Force est de constater que","2":"Je suis convaincu que"},pool:["Force est de constater que","Je suis convaincu que","Il me semble que","À mon avis"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"In a formal debate, which strategy is recommended?",opts:["Only use il me semble que","Start with your strongest claim immediately","Start soft and build to stronger claims","Avoid expressing any opinion"],ans:"Start soft and build to stronger claims",hint:"Good debaters ___ momentum gradually."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Je suis convaincu","Il me semble","À mon avis","Force est de constater"],hint:"We need a phrase expressing strong personal conviction.",s:"{1} que cette réforme améliorera le système éducatif.",a:["Je suis convaincu","Je suis convaincue"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which expression is the MOST formal way to state your opinion?",opts:["Moi, je trouve que","À mon avis","Je pense que","Force est de constater que"],ans:"Force est de constater que",hint:"This impersonal construction avoids first person entirely and sounds institutional."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Selon","D'après","Pour","À"],hint:"A one-word formal preposition meaning according to that precedes a source.",s:"{1} les experts, cette politique aura des effets positifs à long terme.",a:["Selon"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Selon moi, il faudrait investir davantage.' What register is this?",opts:["Semi-formal to formal","Very informal","Slang","Academic only"],ans:"Semi-formal to formal",hint:"This expression works in meetings, essays, and discussions."}
  ]},
  {id:"fre28l8",title:"Révision: convaincre",icon:"🏆",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Révision: convaincre et argumenter",desc:"Combine all discourse markers and argumentation skills in this comprehensive review.",goals:["Use sequencing, addition, contrast, and cause markers together","Structure a complete argument","Choose the right register for each context"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which sequence of markers correctly structures a three-part argument?",opts:["D'abord... ensuite... enfin","Enfin... d'abord... puis","Cependant... de plus... en premier lieu","Par conséquent... car... d'abord"],ans:"D'abord... ensuite... enfin",hint:"Think about the natural order from first to last."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Cependant","De plus","En effet","Car"],hint:"We need a word that introduces a contrasting problem.",s:"Le projet est ambitieux. {1}, il manque de financement.",a:["Cependant","Toutefois","Néanmoins"]},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"Acknowledge, then contrast, then draw a consequence.",s:"{1}, ce plan a du potentiel. {2}, il comporte des risques. {3}, une approche prudente s'impose.",blanks:{"1":"Certes","2":"Cependant","3":"Par conséquent"},pool:["Certes","Cependant","Par conséquent","De plus"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which marker best introduces an undeniable observation in formal debate?",opts:["À mon avis","Force est de constater que","Il me semble que","Selon moi"],ans:"Force est de constater que",hint:"This expression implies the evidence leaves no room for doubt."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Bien que","Même si","Malgré","Certes"],hint:"We need a concession marker followed by the subjunctive.",s:"{1} les résultats soient encourageants, il reste du travail.",a:["Bien que","Quoique"]},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"de plus",src:"moreover"},{trg:"c'est pourquoi",src:"that is why"},{trg:"en revanche",src:"on the other hand"},{trg:"puisque",src:"since"},{trg:"d'où",src:"hence"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'L'auteur réfute ces arguments.' What does the author do?",opts:["Ignores the arguments","Supports the arguments","Systematically disproves the arguments","Repeats the arguments"],ans:"Systematically disproves the arguments",hint:"This verb means to counter and dismantle claims."},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"Three steps of a structured presentation in order.",s:"{1}, je présente le contexte. {2}, j'expose les arguments. {3}, je propose une synthèse.",blanks:{"1":"D'abord","2":"Ensuite","3":"Enfin"},pool:["D'abord","Ensuite","Enfin","Cependant"]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["avance","réfute","conclut","nuance"],hint:"The researcher is proposing something for consideration.",s:"Le chercheur {1} une hypothèse intéressante sur le changement climatique.",a:["avance"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"In a dissertation, what does the synthèse do?",opts:["Introduces new unrelated topics","Repeats the thèse","Rejects the antithèse entirely","Resolves the debate with a balanced perspective"],ans:"Resolves the debate with a balanced perspective",hint:"This section goes beyond simple agreement or disagreement."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Puisque","Car","C'est pourquoi","Par conséquent"],hint:"The reading is already done, a known fact to both speakers.",s:"{1} tu as déjà lu le rapport, commençons la discussion.",a:["Puisque"]},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"Acknowledge, contrast, then derive a consequence.",s:"{1}, cette mesure est populaire. {2}, elle coûte cher. {3} la nécessité d'un compromis.",blanks:{"1":"Certes","2":"Toutefois","3":"D'où"},pool:["Certes","Toutefois","D'où","Ensuite"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which pair correctly contrasts two facts using direct opposition?",opts:["Le nord est froid. En revanche, le sud est chaud.","Le nord est froid. De plus, le sud est chaud.","Le nord est froid. En effet, le sud est chaud.","Le nord est froid. Car le sud est chaud."],ans:"Le nord est froid. En revanche, le sud est chaud.",hint:"We need a marker that sets two things directly against each other."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["nuancer","réfuter","affirmer","conclure"],hint:"We want to add subtlety, not reject entirely.",s:"Je voudrais {1} cette affirmation: elle est vraie en partie seulement.",a:["nuancer"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which combination would you use to build a persuasive paragraph? 'The economy is growing. ___, unemployment persists. ___, new policies are needed.'",opts:["De plus... Car","Cependant... C'est pourquoi","En effet... Ensuite","Par ailleurs... D'abord"],ans:"Cependant... C'est pourquoi",hint:"First contrast the good news, then draw a consequence."},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"Express opinion, add a reservation, then conclude with action.",s:"{1} moi, cette réforme est nécessaire. {2}, elle doit être mieux préparée. {3}, je propose un report de six mois.",blanks:{"1":"Selon","2":"Toutefois","3":"Par conséquent"},pool:["Selon","Toutefois","Par conséquent","En effet"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"You are writing a formal essay conclusion. Which verb best fits: 'Pour ___, les avantages l'emportent sur les inconvénients.'?",opts:["réfuter","avancer","conclure","nuancer"],ans:"conclure",hint:"This is the final summary of your entire argument."}
  ]},
  {id:"fre28l_disp",title:"Résoudre un conflit",icon:"🤝",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Resolving Disputes and Mediating",desc:"Learn to mediate conflicts diplomatically in French: expressing disagreement politely, finding compromises, and restoring trust. Essential for DELF B2 speaking tasks.",goals:["Express disagreement politely","Propose compromises","Use diplomatic French in conflict situations"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"le conflit",src:"conflict",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Un conflit = a disagreement between people or groups.\nPlural: les conflits.",example:"A: Il y a un conflit entre les deux collègues.\nB: Oui, ce conflit dure depuis des semaines.",exampleSrc:"A: There is a conflict between the two colleagues.\nB: Yes, this conflict has been going on for weeks.",funFact:"From Latin 'conflictus' (collision). English 'conflict' is a direct cognate, borrowed via Old French."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"le compromis",src:"compromise",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Un compromis = an agreement where both sides give up something.\nTrouver un compromis = to reach a compromise.",example:"A: On ne peut pas trouver de solution?\nB: Il faut trouver un compromis acceptable pour tous.",exampleSrc:"A: Can't we find a solution?\nB: We need to find a compromise acceptable to everyone.",funFact:"From Latin 'compromissum' (mutual promise). French diplomacy has long relied on the word; it entered English directly from French in the 15th century."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"le malentendu",src:"misunderstanding",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Un malentendu = a situation where someone is misunderstood.\nMal (badly) + entendu (heard/understood).",example:"A: Vous vous disputez vraiment?\nB: Non, c'est juste un malentendu. On va clarifier.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you really arguing?\nB: No, it's just a misunderstanding. We'll clarify.",funFact:"Built from 'mal' (badly) and 'entendre' (to hear/understand). The word perfectly captures how conflicts often start: something heard badly."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"résoudre",src:"to resolve",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Résoudre un problème = to resolve a problem.\nPast participle: résolu. Irregular verb.",example:"A: Comment résoudre ce problème?\nB: On peut résoudre ce conflit avec une bonne communication.",exampleSrc:"A: How do we resolve this problem?\nB: We can resolve this conflict with good communication.",funFact:"From Latin 'resolvere' (to loosen). English 'resolve' and 'resolution' are direct cognates."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"servir de médiateur",src:"to mediate / to act as mediator",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Servir de médiateur = to act as a neutral third party.\nAlso: jouer le rôle de médiateur.",example:"A: Qui va gérer ce conflit?\nB: Je peux servir de médiateur entre les deux parties.",exampleSrc:"A: Who will handle this conflict?\nB: I can mediate between the two parties.",funFact:"'Médiateur' shares its root with Latin 'medius' (middle). A mediator literally stands in the middle between two sides."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"s'excuser",src:"to apologize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Reflexive verb. Je m'excuse = I apologize.\nStronger than 'pardon'. Use sincerely in conflicts.",example:"A: Tu as parlé trop durement.\nB: Tu as raison. Je dois m'excuser pour ce que j'ai dit.",exampleSrc:"A: You spoke too harshly.\nB: You're right. I need to apologize for what I said.",funFact:"From Latin 'excusare' (to free from blame). English 'excuse' is a direct cognate borrowed from French."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"pardonner",src:"to forgive",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Pardonner quelqu'un = to forgive someone.\nPardonner à quelqu'un = also correct. Formal register.",example:"A: Tu lui en veux encore?\nB: Non, je peux pardonner. La relation est plus importante.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you still upset with him?\nB: No, I can forgive. The relationship is more important.",funFact:"From Old French 'pardonner', from 'par' (thoroughly) and 'donner' (to give). English 'pardon' was borrowed directly from French."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Diplomatic language in French conflicts",text:"French has a rich register for handling disagreements without aggression.\n\nSteps for diplomatic resolution:\n1. Name the problem: Il y a un malentendu / un conflit.\n2. Propose a mediator: Quelqu'un peut servir de médiateur.\n3. Find middle ground: Cherchons un compromis.\n4. Apologize sincerely: Je dois m'excuser.\n5. Forgive and restore: Je te pardonne.\n\nIn French professional culture, acknowledging a malentendu quickly prevents escalation."},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which word means a neutral third party who helps resolve a dispute?",opts:["le compromis","le médiateur","le malentendu","le conflit"],ans:"le médiateur",hint:"This person stands in the middle between two sides."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["résoudre","pardonner","s'excuser","servir"],hint:"We need the infinitive meaning 'to resolve' a problem.",s:"Il faut {1} ce conflit rapidement.",a:["résoudre"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'C'est juste un malentendu.' What does this sentence mean?",opts:["It's just a compromise","It's just a misunderstanding","It's just a conflict","It's just an apology"],ans:"It's just a misunderstanding",hint:"The word combines 'mal' (badly) and 'entendu' (heard)."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["compromis","conflit","malentendu","médiateur"],hint:"Both sides give up something to reach this.",s:"Les deux parties ont trouvé un {1} acceptable.",a:["compromis"]},
        {type:"match",pairs:[
          {trg:"le conflit",src:"conflict"},
          {trg:"le compromis",src:"compromise"},
          {trg:"le malentendu",src:"misunderstanding"},
          {trg:"résoudre",src:"to resolve"},
          {trg:"pardonner",src:"to forgive"}
        ]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["m'excuser","pardonner","servir","résoudre"],hint:"I need to say sorry for what I said.",s:"Je dois {1} pour mes paroles.",a:["m'excuser"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"What does 'servir de médiateur' mean in a conflict situation?",opts:["To cause a conflict","To forgive both sides","To act as a neutral third party","To propose a compromise alone"],ans:"To act as a neutral third party",hint:"This person stands between the two sides without taking either position."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["pardonner","résoudre","s'excuser","médiateur"],hint:"To forgive someone and move forward.",s:"Je peux {1} si tu reconnais ton erreur.",a:["pardonner"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"A colleague says 'Je dois m'excuser auprès de toi.' What will they do?",opts:["Forgive you","Mediate a conflict","Propose a compromise","Apologize to you"],ans:"Apologize to you",hint:"This reflexive verb means to offer an apology."}
  ]},
  {id:"fre28l9",title:"Ce qui compte pour moi",icon:"💭",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Writing About Personal Significance",desc:"Learn to write about meaningful experiences, memories, and values in French. Essential for DELF B2 autobiographical writing and personal reflections.",goals:["Express what matters to you","Reflect on formative memories","Describe your personal values"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"signifier",src:"to mean / to signify",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Used for abstract meaning, not physical signs.\nsignifier quelque chose à quelqu'un = to mean something to someone.",example:"A: Ce voyage a beaucoup signifié pour toi?\nB: Oui, il a tout signifié. C'était inoubliable.",exampleSrc:"A: Did this trip mean a lot to you?\nB: Yes, it meant everything. It was unforgettable.",funFact:"From Latin 'significare' (to show by sign). English 'signify' and 'significant' are direct cognates."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"le souvenir",src:"memory (a specific remembered event)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Un souvenir = a specific memory or keepsake.\nDo not confuse with 'la mémoire' (memory as a faculty).\nPlural: les souvenirs.",example:"A: Ce souvenir est très important pour moi.\nB: Quel souvenir gardes-tu de cette période?",exampleSrc:"A: This memory is very important to me.\nB: What memory do you keep from that period?",funFact:"From 'souvenir' (to come to mind again). In everyday French, 'un souvenir' can also mean a souvenir or keepsake you buy on a trip."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"bouleverser",src:"to deeply move / to overwhelm emotionally",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Stronger than 'émouvoir'. Implies being turned upside down.\nbouleverset par = overwhelmed by.",example:"A: Ce film t'a bouleversé?\nB: Oui, il m'a vraiment bouleversé. Je n'ai pas pu dormir.",exampleSrc:"A: Did this film deeply move you?\nB: Yes, it really overwhelmed me. I couldn't sleep.",funFact:"From 'boulevards' (wide streets), via 'bouleverser' = to overturn. The image is of a city turned upside down."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"inoubliable",src:"unforgettable",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"In- (not) + oubliable (forgettable). Invariable in form.\nUsed for memories, experiences, people.",example:"A: C'était une expérience inoubliable pour toi?\nB: Absolument inoubliable. Je m'en souviendrai toujours.",exampleSrc:"A: Was it an unforgettable experience for you?\nB: Absolutely unforgettable. I will always remember it.",funFact:"Built on 'oublier' (to forget), which comes from Latin 'oblitare'. English 'oblivion' shares the same root."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"la valeur",src:"value (abstract principle)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Use for personal or moral values, not prices.\nMes valeurs = my values. Plural: les valeurs.",example:"A: Quelle valeur compte le plus pour toi?\nB: Pour moi, la valeur la plus importante, c'est la sincérité.",exampleSrc:"A: Which value matters most to you?\nB: For me, the most important value is sincerity.",funFact:"From Latin 'valere' (to be strong, to be worth). English 'valor' and 'valid' share the same root."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"façonner",src:"to shape / to mold (character or identity)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Figurative: to shape a person's character or outlook.\nLiteral use: to shape clay or material.",example:"A: Qu'est-ce qui t'a façonné?\nB: Mon enfance m'a façonné. Ces années ont tout changé.",exampleSrc:"A: What has shaped you?\nB: My childhood shaped me. Those years changed everything.",funFact:"From 'façon' (manner, way). Also used literally for a craftsman shaping wood or clay. The figurative sense is very common in reflective writing."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"l'émotion",src:"emotion / feeling",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Une émotion = a single emotion. Les émotions = emotions in general.\nStronger than 'sentiment', which is a longer-lasting state.",example:"A: Tu as ressenti une émotion forte en lisant ça?\nB: Oui, une émotion très profonde. Difficile à décrire.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you feel a strong emotion reading that?\nB: Yes, a very deep emotion. Hard to describe.",funFact:"From Latin 'emovere' (to move out). An emotion literally moves you out of your normal state. English 'emotion' is a direct cognate."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Writing personal reflections in French",text:"For DELF B2 autobiographical tasks, use these structures:\n\n1. Ce qui m'a le plus marqué(e), c'est... (What marked me most is...)\n2. Cela m'a appris que... (That taught me that...)\n3. Ces expériences m'ont façonné(e) en tant que personne. (These experiences shaped me as a person.)\n\nBalance concrete memories (souvenirs) with abstract values (valeurs) for a rich personal essay."},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which word describes being deeply moved or overwhelmed by emotion?",opts:["façonner","bouleverser","signifier","inoubliable"],ans:"bouleverser",hint:"Think of being turned upside down by a powerful feeling"},
        {type:"fb",opts:["signifié","façonné","bouleversé","inoubliable"],hint:"The trip had deep personal meaning for her",s:"Ce voyage a beaucoup {1} pour elle.",a:["signifié"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"You want to say a childhood memory 'shaped' your personality. Which verb do you use?",opts:["signifier","bouleverser","façonner","inoubliable"],ans:"façonner",hint:"Think of a craftsman molding clay into a form"},
        {type:"fb",opts:["émotion","souvenir","valeur","façon"],hint:"A specific event remembered from the past, not the general faculty of memory",s:"Ce {1} est resté gravé dans ma mémoire.",a:["souvenir"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Your friend says an experience 'a tout signifié' for her. What does she mean?",opts:["It meant nothing to her","It overwhelmed her","It meant everything to her","It was forgettable"],ans:"It meant everything to her",hint:"The verb comes from a root meaning 'to give meaning to'. Tout means the complete totality."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["valeur","souvenir","émotion","façon"],hint:"An abstract moral principle like honesty or courage",s:"La {1} que je respecte le plus, c'est le courage.",a:["valeur"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which adjective means 'unforgettable'?",opts:["inoubliable","bouleversant","façonné","signifiant"],ans:"inoubliable",hint:"In- (not) + oubliable (forgettable)"},
        {type:"fb",opts:["émotion","valeur","souvenir","façon"],hint:"A feeling that moves you out of your normal state",s:"Cette musique provoque une {1} très profonde en moi.",a:["émotion"]},
        {type:"match",pairs:[
          {trg:"signifier",src:"to mean / signify"},
          {trg:"le souvenir",src:"a specific memory"},
          {trg:"bouleverser",src:"to deeply move / overwhelm"},
          {trg:"inoubliable",src:"unforgettable"},
          {trg:"la valeur",src:"a personal value"},
          {trg:"façonner",src:"to shape / mold"},
          {trg:"l'émotion",src:"emotion / feeling"}
        ]}
  ]}
, COVERAGE_U28]};
